description.value: Seven women toss Napoleon in a blanket. He flies into the air, wearing his hat; he says: "Oh! that I were safe in Egypt!" His sabre lies broken on the ground. The women say: [1] "Up with him to the Shies [sic]"; "Give him plenty of it"; "He delights in high Stations!" [2] "Pauvre diable!!! is that the Hero who is to conquer England!!!" [3] "We'll toss your Soul out of you!" [4] "Up with him again!" [5] "You sent my Sweetheart to St Domingo!" [see BMSat 9842]. [6] "Well Bunny have you built any more Castles since you've been up in the Air! Or will you [sic] some more Conscripts to help you." [7] "Well, are you come to your Senses yet;? Can you behave peaceably."  In the background (left) a Dutchman and a Spanish don sit together at a table. Both watch the scene, the Dutchman, who is smoking, with delight.  29 May 1803  Hand-coloured etching

description.value: In a room decorated in classical and Egyptian styles, Augustus sits on the left, left hand raised, refuting Cleopatra's justification for her actions. Cleopatra, reclining on a pallet-bed, points to the statue of Caesar in the background. A medallion of Cleopatra, shown with Antony in Ptolemaic royal style, is partially exposed by the drape behind her. While trying to conceal her possessions from Augustus, her ploys flounder as Seleucus, her steward, emerges from the background with the inventory of them. Behind her stand two attendants, on the far right is a table with an ornate box and a classical statue on the left; published state.  1784  Mezzotint
